Background

Supermarkets play a crucial role in our daily lives by providing us with the necessary groceries and household items. The retail industry is constantly evolving with changing consumer demands, technological advancements, and economic fluctuations. Therefore, it is imperative for supermarkets to optimize their operations to stay competitive, improve customer satisfaction, and maximize profits.

Problem statement

1.To analyze the supermarket’s sales and order management data to identify customers buying patterns and trends.

2. To analyze supermarket’s 1) Most popular meal 2) Sales trends 4) Order management. It can help identify which products are in high demand, which products are slow-moving, which products are not selling at all and delivery time to serve the orders. This analysis can be used to optimize the supermarket’s order management, pricing strategy, and marketing campaigns.

Project Proposal

We will create a descriptive model to identify trends and patterns in customer behavior and product sales. This will help the store better understand their customers and optimize their orders, pricing, and marketing strategies to improve sales and customer satisfaction.

Analysis Questions

1. What are the top-selling products and how does their sales volume and revenue compare?

2. What are the busiest days and times for each store, and how can the supermarket chain optimize their delivery time to meet demand?

3. Are there any product categories that are consistently underperforming, and how can the supermarket chain address this issue?

4. Can the supermarket chain identify any patterns in customer behavior, such as recurring purchases or differences in purchasing behavior across different customer segments?

5. How effective are the store’s pricing strategies, and are there opportunities to improve margins or offer more competitive prices?

Academic Integrity

Integrity means to make choices according to a certain set of values.

Academic integrity means to be guided by shared values and norms of behaviour in all aspects of one’s academic work.

St. Clair College is committed to the six fundamental values of academic integrity: honesty, trust, fairness, respect, responsibility, and courage. Applying these values can help guide students to make good choices about how to approach their schoolwork. Academic integrity means putting those values into practice and being accountable.

Faculty, staff and students each play an important role in building and maintaining a culture of academic integrity. All members of our college community have a shared responsibility to uphold the principles of academic integrity so that the teaching-learning relationship is built on mutual trust and respect, and that we maintain an honest and fair learning environment.

Academic integrity is integral to a student’s academic success. The habits that students develop on their academic journey while at St. Clair College will carry them not only through their program of study but also into the workplace.

The geom_col() function is used to create a column chart, and the mapping argument is used to map the CompanyName variable to the x-axis and the OrderValuesPerCompany variable to the y-axis.

Overall, these two blocks of code are used to identify the top companies in the “OrderLeads” dataset based on their total order values and create a visualization to display this information.

#7 Plot showing a relationship between two variables

Description:The first block of code groups the “MergedOrders” dataset by SalesRep variable using group_by() function.

The second block of code calculates the total sales order value for each sales representative using summarise() function, then arranges the resulting dataset in descending order of sales order value and extracts the top 10 sales representatives with the highest sales order values.

The third block of code creates a scatter plot using ggplot to display the sales order value for each of the top 10 sales representatives.

The ggplot() function initializes a plot object, and the aes() function is used to map the SalesRep variable to the x-axis and the SalesOrderValue variable to the y-axis.The geom_jitter() function is used to add jitter to the data points, making it easier to see overlapping points. The size argument sets the size of the jittered points, and the color argument sets the color of the points to “springgreen”.The ylim() function sets the limits of the y-axis to focus on the range of sales order values of interest.The geom_text() function is used to add labels to the data points, displaying the corresponding sales order value for each sales representative. The label argument specifies the values to be displayed, and the vjust argument adjusts the vertical positioning of the labels

Overall, these three blocks of code are used to identify the top 10 sales representatives in the “MergedOrders” dataset based on their sales order value and create a visualization to display this information. The scatter plot allows us to see the distribution of sales order values across the top 10 sales representatives and identify any patterns or outliers.

Plot 7

library(readxl)
MergedOrders <- read_excel("~/Desktop/Gurjinder/Data Analytics for Business/DAB501 Rstudio/Project 1/MergedOrders.xlsx")
# Grouped the data based on SalesRep
sales1 <- group_by(MergedOrders,SalesRep)
# Summarised added SalesOrderValue column, And extracted top 10 salesRep wrt SalesOrder
sales2 <- summarise(sales1,
                   SalesOrderValue = sum(OrderValue))
sales2 <- arrange(sales2,desc(SalesOrderValue))
sales3 <- sales2[1:10,]
ggplot(sales3,aes(x=SalesRep,y=SalesOrderValue))+
  geom_jitter(size = 4,color="springgreen")+
  ylim(1700000, 2500000)+
  geom_text(aes(label=SalesOrderValue), vjust = -1.2)+
  theme_classic()+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust = 1))+
labs(x="Order Value", y="Sales Rep" , title = "Revenue generated by Sales Rep",
         caption = "Figure 7. Plot displaying information between two variables i.e. Sales Revenue by Sales Rep")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust=0.5,face = "bold"),plot.caption = element_text(hjust=0.3,face = "bold"),axis.text.x = element_text(face = "bold"),,axis.text.y = element_text(face = "bold"))

#8 Plot showing a relationship between 4 variables using Facets

Description:The code creates a scatter plot with colored points and facets using ggplot. The x-axis represents the TypeofMeal variable, and the y-axis represents the MealPrice variable from the MergedOrders dataset. The color of the points is determined by the Meal served Year variable, and the fill color is determined by the Order Placed Year variable.

The geom_point() function adds the scatter plot layer to the plot object created by ggplot(). The facet_wrap() function is used to create facets based on the Meals_Served_Per_Year variable, with each row containing 5 facets and each column containing 8 facets.

The tilde ~ symbol in facet_wrap(~ Meals_Served_Per_Year, nrow=5, ncol=8) indicates that the variable following the tilde should be used to create facets. The nrow and ncol arguments specify the number of rows and columns to use for the facets.

Overall, this code is used to create a visualization of the relationship between TypeofMeal and MealPrice variables with the added feature of color-coding and faceting based on the Meal served Yearly and Order Placed Yearly variables. This allows us to see how the relationship between the variables may have changed over time and whether there are any patterns or trends within and across the different years.

Plot 8

# updated column name
colnames(MergedOrders)[which(names(MergedOrders) == "YYYY Meal served Year")] <- "Meals_Served_Per_Year"
#Filtered the Tyoe of meals

f <- ggplot(data = MergedOrders1, aes(x=MergedOrders1$`TypeofMeal`, y=MergedOrders1$`MealPrice`, color = Meals_Served_Per_Year, fill= MergedOrders1$`YYYY Order Placed Year`)) +

  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust=0.5))+

#9 Competition Plot

Description: The code first groups the MergedOrders dataset by SalesRep and CompanyName and then filters only the converted orders using the filter() function.

The code then summarizes the filtered data by calculating the sum of OrderValue for each SalesRep and CompanyName using the summarise() function. The resulting dataset CompanyPerSalesRep1 is then arranged in descending order based on the SalesOrderValue column, and the top 12 SalesRep with respect to the CompanyName are extracted.

The code creates a scatter plot with differently sized points using ggplot. The x-axis represents the SalesRep variable, and the y-axis represents the CompanyName variable from the CompanyPerSalesRep1 dataset. The size of the points is determined by the SalesOrderValue variable.The geom_point() function adds the scatter plot layer to the plot object created by ggplot(). The color argument specifies the color of the points to be “multicolor”.

Overall, this code is used to create a visualization of the top 12 Sales Reps and their respective companies, based on the SalesOrderValue variable. The scatter plot with differently sized points allows us to compare the SalesOrderValue across different Sales Reps and their respective companies. The larger the size of the point, the higher the SalesOrderValue for that particular Sales Rep and company.

Plot 9

# Grouped with SalesRep & CompanyName and filtered only converted orders
CompanyPerSalesRep <- group_by(MergedOrders,SalesRep,CompanyName)
CompanyPerSalesRep <- filter(CompanyPerSalesRep, Converted == 1)
#Summarised with Sum of OrderValue and extracted Top ASlesrep wrt to Company
CompanyPerSalesRep1 <- summarise(CompanyPerSalesRep,
                   SalesOrderValue = sum(OrderValue))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'SalesRep'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
CompanyPerSalesRep1<- arrange(CompanyPerSalesRep1,desc(SalesOrderValue))
CompanyPerSalesRep1 <- CompanyPerSalesRep1[1:12,]
ggplot(CompanyPerSalesRep1, aes(x= SalesRep, y=CompanyName, size = SalesOrderValue, color=SalesRep))+
  geom_point()+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust = 1))+
labs(x="Order Value", y="Sales Rep" , title = "Revenue generated by Sales Rep",
         caption = "Figure 9. Plot displaying information about Revenue generated by Sales Rep")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust=0.5))+

Answers to the following questions

1.In what ways do you think data visualization is important to understanding a data set?

Data visualization helps in understanding data sets by providing a clear and concise representation of complex data, allowing individuals to identify patterns, trends, and relationships that may not be immediately apparent from raw data. It allows people to explore and analyze data in a more intuitive and efficient way, helping them make informed decisions and communicate findings effectively. Data visualization is also useful in identifying outliers or anomalies, which may indicate errors or anomalies in the data set. Overall, data visualization plays a crucial role in helping individuals understand, interpret, and communicate complex data.

2.In what ways do you think data visualization is important to communicating important aspects of a data set?

  • Provides a clear and concise representation of complex data: Visual representations like graphs, charts, and diagrams help to simplify complex data and present it in a way that is easy to understand.

  • Helps to identify trends and patterns: Data visualization can help to identify patterns and trends in data that may not be immediately apparent when looking at raw numbers or text.

  • Increases engagement and understanding: Visual representations of data are often more engaging and memorable than text-based descriptions, leading to better comprehension and retention of information.

  • Facilitates decision-making: By presenting data in a clear and concise way, decision-makers can quickly and easily analyze the information and make informed decisions.

  • Encourages exploration and discovery: Data visualization can inspire curiosity and encourage users to explore data sets further, leading to new insights and discoveries.

  • Overall, data visualization plays a crucial role in making complex data accessible and understandable, enabling decision-makers to make informed choices, and encouraging exploration and discovery.

3.What role does your integrity as an analyst play when creating a data visualization for communicating results to others?

The integrity of an analyst determines how accurately and truthfully the data is presented. It is essential to represent the data honestly, without manipulating or distorting it to fit a particular narrative. By being transparent and honest with the data, an analyst can build trust with their audience and ensure that decisions made based on the visualization are sound and reliable. Therefore, an analyst’s integrity is crucial in establishing credibility and trust with their audience, ensuring that the data presented is accurate, unbiased, and useful.

4.How many variables do you think you can successfully represent in a visualization? What happens when you exceed this number?

The number of variables that can be successfully represented in a visualization depends on various factors such as the complexity of the data, the type of visualization used, and the target audience. Generally, it is recommended to keep the number of variables between 3 to 7, beyond which it becomes difficult to interpret and comprehend the visualization. When you exceed this number, the visualization may become cluttered, confusing, and misleading, making it difficult for the audience to understand the key insights and patterns in the data.
